 Global World provide insights into key themes impacting local governance in two federations with much in common historically, culturally, and politically: Australia and Canada.These essays examine changes in the Australian and Canadian systems through four thematic lenses: citizen participation in government systems, the restructuring and reform of local governments, the use of performance measures and management systems in the administration of local governments, and the relations of local governments within higher levels of governments. Unique in its thematic selection and in its compare-and-contrast structure, Local Government in a Global World provides a valuable reference for those seeking to understand how effective local government is structured and managed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aComparative government. 0aGlobalization. 0aLocal governmentzAustralia. 0aMunicipal governmentzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aAgocs, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAulich, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunet-Jailly, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Katherine A. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKloot, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPhillips, Susan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSancton, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSansom, Graham, econ